04390nam a22005295i 9780674919440DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749194407 a10.4159/97806749194402doi  a(DE-B1597)501450  a(OCoLC)1027218801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBL240.3b.W458 2018 7aREL1060002bisacsh04a201/.652231 aWhite, Christopher G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOther Worlds :bSpirituality and the Search for Invisible Dimensions /cChristopher G. White. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (340 p.) :b19 halftones, 15 line illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Science, the Supernatural, and Higher Realms -- t1. Edwin Abbott’s Otherworldly Visions -- t2. The Man Who Saw the Fourth Dimension -- t3. New Heaven, New Earth -- t4. Cathedrals without Walls -- t5. Max Weber and the Art of an Invisible Geometry -- t6. The Spacetime of Dreams -- t7. Mirrors, Doorways, and Otherworldly Openings -- t8. Madeleine L’Engle Disturbs the Universe -- t9. One Step Beyond -- tConclusion: The Astonishing Afterlife of the Square -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat do modern multiverse theories and spiritualist séances have in common? Not much, it would seem. One is an elaborate scientific theory developed by the world’s most talented physicists. The other is a spiritual practice widely thought of as backward, the product of a mystical world view fading under the modern scientific gaze. But Christopher G. White sees striking similarities. He does not claim that séances or other spiritual practices are science. Yet he points to ways that both spiritual practices and scientific speculation about multiverses and invisible dimensions are efforts to peer into the hidden elements and even the existential meaning of the universe. Other Worlds examines how the idea that the universe has multiple, invisible dimensions has inspired science fiction, fantasy novels, films, modern art, and all manner of spiritual thought reaching well beyond the realm of formal religion. Drawing on a range of international archives, White analyzes how writers, artists, filmmakers, televangelists, and others have used the scientific idea of invisible dimensions to make supernatural phenomena such as ghosts and miracles seem more reasonable and make spiritual beliefs possible again for themselves and others. Many regard scientific ideas as disenchanting and secularizing, but Other Worlds shows that these ideas—creatively appropriated in such popular forms as C. S. Lewis’s Chronicles of Narnia, the art of Salvador Dalí, or the books of the counterculture physicist “Dr. Quantum”—restore a sense that the world is greater than anything our eyes can see, helping to forge an unexpected kind of spirituality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArts and religionzGreat Britain. 0aArts and religionzUnited States. 0aReligion and sciencezGreat Britain. 0aReligion and sciencezUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067491944040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919440.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles